      (¯4○R)  INV∆EQUIV  5○¯6○R

⍝ lrm p. 81
      X← 9○R   ⍝ real R
      Y←11○R   ⍝ imag R
      I←0J1
      S¯4← ¯1+2×(X≥0) ∨ (¯1<X)∧(X<0)∧(Y=0)                     ⍝ sign ¯4○
      S¯8← ¯1+2×((X>0)∧(Y>0))∨((X=0)∧(Y>1))∨((X<0)∧(Y≥0))      ⍝ sign ¯8○

      ( 0○R) INV∆EQUIV (1-R⋆2)⋆.5                                  ⍝
      ( 1○R) INV∆EQUIV ((1○X)×(6○Y)) + I×(2○X)×(5○Y)               ⍝ SINZ R
      (¯1○R) INV∆EQUIV -I×¯5○I×R                                   ⍝ ASINZ R
      ( 2○R) INV∆EQUIV ((2○X)×(6○Y)) - I×(1○X)×(5○Y)               ⍝ COSZ R
      (¯2○R) INV∆EQUIV (.5×○1) - ¯1○R                              ⍝ ACOSZ R
      ( 3○R) INV∆EQUIV ((1○X)+I×(2○X)×(7○Y))÷(2○X)-I×(1○X)×(7○Y)   ⍝ TANZ R
      ( 4○R) INV∆EQUIV (1+R⋆2)⋆.5                                  ⍝ ATANZ R
      (¯4○R) INV∆EQUIV S¯4 × (¯1 + R⋆2)⋆.5
      ( 5○R) INV∆EQUIV -I×1○I×R                                    ⍝ SINHZ R
      (¯5○R) INV∆EQUIV -I×¯1○I×R                                   ⍝ ASINHZ R
      ( 6○R) INV∆EQUIV 2○I×R                                       ⍝ COSHZ R
      (¯6○R) INV∆EQUIV ⍟(R+¯4○R)                                   ⍝ ACOSHZ R
      ( 7○R) INV∆EQUIV -I×3○I×R                                    ⍝ TANHZ R
      (¯7○R) INV∆EQUIV -I×¯3○I×R                                   ⍝ ATANHZ R
      ( 8○R) INV∆EQUIV S¯8 × (¯1-R⋆2)⋆.5
      (¯8○R) INV∆EQUIV -8○R

⍝ lrm p. 188:   (0≠L)/R   ←→    ⊃,/L⊂R

COMMENT «««

      first of all, lrm p.188 says: "For any appropriate L and R:". Thus the
      above invariant stated on is wrong for some L and R. The most
      problematic cases seem to be those with empty results

      For example:

      L←1 0 0 1 ◊ R ← 0 2 4⍴42
      ⍝
      In IBM APL2 we get:

      ⍴ (0≠L)/R  gives 0 2 2
      ⍴ ⊃,/L⊂R   gives 0 2 0

      The mismatch apparently occurs for empty L⊂R and we map these
      case to non-empty R below.
        »»»

      R←ANY_I ∣ 1000   ⍝ avoid large ints to make errors more readable
      R←((1⌈⍴⍴R)↑(⍴R),0)⍴R   ⍝ non-scalar R
      R←(1 ⌈⍴R)⍴R            ⍝ make R non-empty
      ⍝
      ⍝        ┌──────────────── rank:       1 (vector)
      ⍝        │  ┌───────────── shape:      random 0 - 20
      ⍝        │  │      ┌────── type:       (100% integer)
      ⍝        │  │      │  ┌─── max. depth: 1
      ⍝        │  │      │  │
      L←⎕RVAL  1 20 (0 100) 1   ⍝ some integers for the partition vector
      L←∣L                      ⍝ L must be nonnegative
      L←4∣L                     ⍝ L shall be small (for longer partitions)
      L←(¯1↑⍴R)⍴L               ⍝ ⍴L must match the last axis of R
      "L:" L
³
      "⍴L:" (⍴L) "≡L:" (≡L)
³
      "⍴R:" (⍴R) "≡R:" (≡R)
³

      Z←L⊂R
COMMENT «««
      the left and/or right side of the invariant (0≠L)/R  ←→  ⊃,/L⊂R might
      fail while L⊂R has succeeded. Catch and pretend success in these cases.
        »»»

      (Z1 Z2)← '1 1' ⎕EA '((0≠L)/R) (⊃,/Z)'

COMMENT «««
      empty results are also misterious. For L←0 or L←, and R←,1 both
      GNU APL and IBM APL 2 return the same result, but the invariant
      does not hold. In this case the right side Z2 should be 0⍴⊂Z2 instead.
        »»»

      (Z1 Z2) ← Z1 Z2 ⊢[(0ϵ⍴Z2) ∨ (0≡Z2) ] 1 1   ⍝ fix empty Z2
      Z1 INV∆EQUIV Z2

      )CHECK BRIEF

      )CLEAR
CLEAR WS

